First, let's find the symmetric difference between A and B (A △ B). The symmetric difference between two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4}
A ∩ B = {2, 3}

A △ B = {1, 4}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference between (A △ B) and C ((A △ B) △ C).

(A △ B) = {1, 4}
C = {3, 4, 5}
(A △ B) ∩ C = {4}

(A △ B) △ C = {1, 3, 5}

Now let's find the symmetric difference between B and C (B △ C).

B = {2, 3, 4}
C = {3, 4, 5}
B ∩ C = {3, 4}

B △ C = {2, 5}

Now let's find the symmetric difference between A and (B △ C) (A △ (B △ C)).

A = {1, 2, 3}
(B △ C) = {2, 5}
A ∩ (B △ C) = {2}

A △ (B △ C) = {1, 3, 5}

So, ((A △ B) △ C) = {1, 3, 5} and (A △ (B △ C)) = {1, 3, 5}.
